The global epidemic of the new crown continues to escalate

The US is on the brink of an outbreak

On March 11, the World Health Organization officially declared the new pneumonia pandemic.

World Health Organization's confirmation represents a serious escalation of the current global outbreak of the new coronavirus and a significant political and economic impact on the world.

As new cases of pneumonia are confirmed around the world, outbreaks in the United States are spreading across the country.

There have been 1,311 confirmed cases in the United States, according to the latest data from the Johns Hopkins University on November 11th.

The number of newly confirmed cases per day has been increasing exponentially, with only a few new cases per day from January to February, to an average of more than 200 new cases per day, bringing the cumulative death toll to 38.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
More and more states in the United States in the face of new crown disease "lost" , Washington State, New York State, California has become the three major disaster areas, many states have declared a state of emergency.

Washington state raised the alert on Feb. 29, and by Feb. 11,366 confirmed cases were at the center of the nation's worst outbreak.

Seattle, in northwestern Washington, is home to a host of global tech giants, including Microsoft, Facebook, Amazon, twitter, Google and Apple, in just a few days, more than companies have announced that their employees have been diagnosed.

According to statistics, the majority of Technology Company employees diagnosed with new crown pneumonia are from the city of Seattle, Microsoft has a total of 3 seattle employees diagnosed, including one from its linkedin business;

Two Facebook employees were infected, one in Seattle and the other in Singapore

Amazon has three employees confirmed, two in Italy, one in Seattle headquarters, Facebook and Amazon have chosen to close their Seattle offices;

A Swiss Google employee has been diagnosed with a new coronavirus, and apple said on the 11th that an employee in its Irish office confirmed the infection. There have been no confirmed cases in the United States.

Unlike China, every state and city in the United States has its own local laws and policies, with the exception of New Rochelle, a hard hit area of New York that has been locked down, the rest of the United States relies on voluntary isolation for high-risk individuals who may have come into contact with newly diagnosed patients.

Without unified monitoring and supervision, the technology giants in the worst-hit areas have chosen "autonomy" to protect their own interests and employees, to curb the outbreak of a more serious situation.

How does the US tech giant "govern itself" ?

1. Twitter was the first to go

Twitter is the first tech giant in the US to aggressively encourage employees to work from home to avoid spreading the new coronavirus.

As early as March 1, the company announced that it would suspend all non-critical business travel and activities. "Our goal is to reduce the possibility of the company and the world spreading the COVID-19 coronavirus, " the statement stressed

"All employees worldwide are encouraged to work from home. Employees in the Hong Kong, Japan and South Korea offices must work from home, " it said in an e-mail to all employees

A spokesman for Twitter also said that more in-depth cleaning and sanitizing of the workplace, as well as more visual reminders, would increase employees'awareness of personal cleanliness and protection.

At the same time, a spokesman for Twitter said all employees, including hourly workers, would be eligible for reimbursement for setting up their own Home Office.

Twitter CEO Jake Dorsey himself canceled a three to six month trip to Africa because of the outbreak. From top management to staff, the height of the new crown disease.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
2. Amazon gets first crack

Amazon, which is based in Washington state, one of the hardest-hit areas, is the first tech giant to have a confirmed case of new pneumonia.

On March 2, Amazon announced that one of its Seattle employees had been diagnosed with the new coronavirus. The employee reportedly returned home sick on February 25 and has not been in or out of the building since.

The company issued a statement immediately, encouraging other symptomatic employees to stay at home and allowing Seattle office workers to work from home until the end of March, and said it would continue to clean the office in depth.

On March 5th Amazon closed its Seattle offices one after another, making it mandatory for all employees to work from home and waiting to hear whether the policy had been extended.

The move comes after Amazon imposed travel restrictions on employees in January and told those who had been to China to work from home in self-imposed isolation for two weeks, seek medical attention if symptoms develop.

3. FACEBOOK closes Seattle Office

On March 5, an employee at Facebook's Seattle office was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia.

Facebook then went into a state of emergency, closing an office in Seattle and encouraging more than 5,000 employees in the Seattle area to work from home until the end of the month, "We have informed our staff and followed the advice of public health officials to put everyone's health and safety first, " the statement said.

For its headquarters in the bay area, Facebook allows employees to work from home as of March 9, and will decide this week whether to extend the hours. Meanwhile, Facebook said it would conduct an online interview.

4. Google policy follows

On March 6, Google's headquarters announced that Bay area employees would be allowed to work from home, and then Google executives sent out a company wide public email telling employees to cancel all major events unless necessary, a detailed travel ban has been imposed on staff travelling to four affected countries, Italy, Iran, South Korea and Japan, and on any visits to offices in Seattle and the San Francisco area.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Google CEO Sundar Pichai warned employees in an internal email on March 9, "everyone should be prepared to work from home at any time given the new coronavirus development, " he said, adding: "bring your laptop home every night. "

For those who have to come to the bay area office, buses and security will operate as usual, but will be timed to meet demand, and deep cleaning will be ensured on a daily basis. While Google said the cafeteria would be open as usual, most of the bay area offices were closed as of March 9, and only three or four main canteens are open, it said, because most people work from home.

5. Sleepless in Seattle

Microsoft, based in Redmond, east of Seattle, is not doing well either. So far, three employees have confirmed new coronavirus infection, all in the headquarters office. One example is an employee of the company's Linkedin Business Unit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Microsoft has announced its own telecommuting policy for the outbreak, requiring employees in the Seattle, wash. , and San Francisco area to work from home until the end of March during the new coronavirus outbreak. It also said it would continue to pay regular hourly rates to those who provide services to Microsoft employees, such as bus drivers, cleaners and cafeteria workers.

At its headquarters alone, Microsoft employs 4,500 hourly workers, and the Redmond campus in Washington state employs 54,000 people, a third of the global workforce.

6. Apple allows telecommuting in "high-density areas. "

According to the latest foreign media reports, on March 10, apple in Ireland Cork Park, an employee confirmed infection with the new coronavirus.

In a public statement this week, Apple Chief Executive Tim Cook called the COVID-19 outbreak "an unprecedented event" and encouraged employees at the company's offices around the world, between March 9 and March 13, "telecommute if your job description allows. ".

It also promised that hourly workers would "continue to be paid the same as they were when business as usual" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Big Tech Conference cancelled or postponed

SXSW, a series of music, Film and Interactive Multimedia Festivals held each March in Austin, Texas, holds a pivotal position in the tech community.

On March 3rd FACEBOOK, twitter, Amazon, apple and Netflix, among others, announced they would not attend the South by Southwest Conference in Austin, Texas, in March.

On the same day, Google announced it was canceling its annual "I / O" conference, Google's most important annual gathering of web developers, at which it has previously shared its latest developments and new products, however, "due to the high level of care for the health and safety of our customers, partners and employees" was cancelled.

Google also announced it was canceling its annual "Google Cloud next" conference on cloud computing.

Similarly, Facebook canceled its F8 developer conference this year and said it would launch some live webcasts of developer related events, though details have not yet been released.

Due to concerns about the global spread of the new coronaviruses, Microsoft has also decided to move this year's MVP summit to an online event scheduled for March 16-20. While Microsoft hasn't said whether its annual Build developer conference will take place on May 1921, the outbreak has certainly cast a pall over the conference.

On March 6th ICLR 2020, the annual gathering in the field of artificial intelligence that was due to take place on April 26th at the Addis Ababa in Ethiopia's capital, was also due to change, with officials saying they were preparing to move this year's event online.

On March 11, two attendees at the RSA Cybersecurity Conference in San Francisco were diagnosed with a new coronavirus, and Amazon announced that it had canceled the April 14 event in San Francisco.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the same day, IBM also announced that it would cancel a live event at the IBM Think 2020 conference in San Francisco in May. Apple's worldwide developers conference (WWDC) , which usually takes place in June, has yet to be officially announced.

You know, in general, developer conferences are very important in the tech industry, and have a very profound impact on the company's overall strategy, but with the impact of the new crown epidemic escalating, the conventions are being canceled or moved online, which is a tough decision for the tech companies.

White House calls tech giants to huddle together for warmth

On March 11, the White House issued an emergency call to Amazon, apple, Facebook, Google, Microsoft and twitter to mobilize technology companies to respond.

"The top priority of the White House right now is the safety and health of the American people. Technology companies should play a key role at this time of total preparedness to fight the epidemic. Today's meeting points out the direction of our efforts in the future, and we will continue to hold relevant discussions,"said the moderator of the meeting, michael Kratsios, the US chief technology officer, said:.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For example, technology companies should take advantage of technology to extract valuable medical information from existing databases. And share data with the government to help the government keep track of the development of the epidemic.

Controlling the rapid spread of disinformation on social media is also a priority for the White House, requiring the active cooperation of Facebook and twitter, and the technology previously used to filter terrorist information may be reused.

In addition, to provide telemedicine, conference and online education technical support to ensure the normal operation of work and study.

Before today's meeting, many technology companies were already actively looking for opportunities to play their part.

Companies such as Google and Amazon have said they will provide information and technical support to the American public on the new coronavirus and assume their social responsibilities to combat the growing threat of the new virus.

Google ads will help people filter out false information about the new coronavirus vaccine.

FACEBOOK has begun deleting fake messages and conspiracy theories, far more aggressively than it has ever done just to flag fake messages. "remove anything labeled false or conspiracy theories by international and local medical authorities. " INSTAGRAM banned many hashtags for spreading misinformation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Amazon has deleted more than a million products that claim to cure or prevent new coronaviruses, and is trying to stop the platform's merchants from taking advantage of the national crisis.

In addition to posting new coronavirus warnings and caveats on the platform, Uber will also close the accounts of drivers who may have been exposed to COVID-19 to ensure the safety of passengers, and the accounts of about 240 users will be temporarily closed by Uber.

Led by Microsoft and Amazon, some seattle-based companies have teamed up with non-profit organizations and government agencies to form foundations, the $2.5 million fund will be used to support institutions that care for people with chronic diseases, uninsured people and health care workers.

Although according to the data, the number of new crown cases in the United States will continue to grow at an alarming rate in the near future, we believe that with the joint efforts of everyone and every enterprise with social responsibility and love, we will be able to help each other through the difficult times, so in the near future, everything will be restored to the original lively and beautiful, people will also because of this sudden epidemic test, close the heart and heart of each other.
